ecoregions contained various amounts of shared climates, there were
isolated cases where ecoregions were <80% shared, although this was
expected whenever high novel or disappeared climates covered the
same ecoregion and climate variable (Figure 6). The Arctic Tundra,
Bering Tundra, and Intermontane Boreal ecoregions contained the
highest overall shared climate distributions in Alaska at 84.9%, 98.28%,
and 75.3%, indicating that these ecoregions are generally less af‐
fected by postglacial climate change (Figure 6). The Coast and Pacific
Mountain Transition ecoregions experienced the lowest amounts of
shared climates at 15.0% and 17.5%, indicating that these ecoregions
are generally more affected by postglacial climate change (Figure 6).
